@page "/"

<PageTitle>Unified Resolution Model</PageTitle>

<div id="top" class="bg-black bg-black-hole vh-50 text-light rounded mt-2">
    <div class="bg-dark bg-opacity-50 h-100 rounded">
        <div class="container row m-0 h-100">
            <div class="col-md-12 m-auto justify-content-center align-self-center">
                <MudText Typo="Typo.h2">
                    Unified Resolution Model
                </MudText>
                <MudText Typo="Typo.subtitle1">
                    A resolution-dependent view of a single underlying structure
                </MudText>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="container mt-2">
    <MudAlert Severity="Severity.Error" Variant="Variant.Filled">
        <p class="m-0 lead">Call to Physicists</p>
        <p>
            This is an independent theoretical framework in development.<br />
            I'm not a physicist by training — but I believe the model offers testable, unifying structure.<br />

            If you're a physicist or researcher in quantum gravity, your critique and insight is welcome.<br />
            📧 Contact details are listed in each paper.
        </p>
    </MudAlert>
</div>

<div id="papers" class="container mt-4">
    <MudPaper Elevation="2">
        <div class="p-2">
            <MudText Typo="Typo.h4">
                Papers
            </MudText>
            <hr />

            <MudAlert Severity="Severity.Normal" Variant="Variant.Outlined" Class="mb-2">
                <p class="m-0">
                    A Unified Resolution Model: Reconciling Loop Quantum Gravity and M-Theory via Layered Magnification
                </p>
                <p class="m-0 small">
                    Published: 2025/07/27
                </p>
                <MudButton Color="Color.Primary" Variant="Variant.Filled" Size="Size.Small" Href="papers/urm_0.pdf">[PDF]View/Download</MudButton>
            </MudAlert>

            <MudAlert Severity="Severity.Normal" Variant="Variant.Outlined" Class="mb-2">
                <p class="m-0">
                    Unified Resolution Model I: A Theoretical and Mathematical Framework for Dimensional Emergence
                </p>
                <p class="m-0 small">
                    Published: 2025/07/27
                </p>
                <MudButton Color="Color.Primary" Variant="Variant.Filled" Size="Size.Small" Href="papers/urm_i.pdf">[PDF]View/Download</MudButton>
            </MudAlert>

            <MudAlert Severity="Severity.Normal" Variant="Variant.Outlined" Class="mb-2">
                <p class="m-0">
                    Unified Resolution Model II: Mathematical Structure and Dimensional Transitions
                </p>
                <p class="m-0 small">
                    Published: 2025/07/28
                </p>
                <MudButton Color="Color.Primary" Variant="Variant.Filled" Size="Size.Small" Href="papers/urm_ii.pdf">[PDF]View/Download</MudButton>
            </MudAlert>
        </div>
    </MudPaper>
</div>


<div id="experiments" class="container mt-4">
    <MudPaper Elevation="2">
        <div class="p-2">
            <MudText Typo="Typo.h4">
                Experiments
            </MudText>
            <hr />
            <MudText Typo="Typo.body1">
                This section will feature proposed experiments aimed at testing predictions of the Unified Resolution Model (URM).
            </MudText>
            <MudText Typo="Typo.body1">
                The goal is to explore whether resolution-dependent physical phenomena can be observed using current or near-future technology.
            </MudText>
            <hr />
            <MudText Typo="Typo.body1">
                🧠 If you're a physicist or researcher interested in contributing to experimental design or interpretation, I’d greatly value your input. Please feel free to reach out.
            </MudText>
        </div>
    </MudPaper>
</div>

<div class="container mt-4" id="overview">
    <MudPaper Elevation="2">
        <div class="p-2">
            <MudText Typo="Typo.h4">
                Overview
            </MudText>
            <hr />

            <div class="row m-0">
                <div class="col-md-4">
                    <MudAlert Severity="Severity.Error" Variant="Variant.Outlined">
                        Not scientifically accurate — conceptual illustration only.
                    </MudAlert>

                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body1">
                        This interactive visualization represents a conceptual model of the Unified Resolution Model.
                    </MudText>
                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body1">
                        As you increase the resolution parameter ρ, the structure appears to evolve — revealing more structure. This illustrates the core URM idea:
                    </MudText>

                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                        <strong>Physical structure and dimensionality are resolution-dependent.</strong><br />
                        At low resolution, reality appears coarse and simple (e.g., like spin networks in Loop Quantum Gravity). As resolution increases, finer and higher-dimensional structures emerge — potentially culminating in the detailed frameworks of M-theory.
                    </MudText>

                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body1">
                        This visual doesn't simulate physics. It's an analogy for how LQG &amp; M-Theory may be describing the same underlying structure at different observational resolutions — much like zooming into a fractal reveals hidden detail.
                    </MudText>
                    <hr />

                    <label>Resolution (ρ): <input type="range" min="0" max="100" value="0" id="resolutionSlider" /></label>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-8">
                    <div id="urm-visual-container" class="h-100" style="min-height:500px"></div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </MudPaper>
</div>

<div class="my-5"></div>